aryat.full:
returns the element E at index I in array A (or dies on out of bounds)
[A I] => [E]

[1 2 3 4 4 0]  => [1]
[1 2 3 4 4 2]  => [3]
[1 2 3 4 4 -1] => [4]  negative index counts from the end
aryat.desc: returns the element E at index I in array A (or dies on out of bounds)

arycat.full:
returns the concatenation of arrays A and B
[A B] => [A+B]

[1 2 3 3 4 5 6 3] => [1 2 3 4 5 6 6]
[7 10 2 5 4 3 3] => [7 10 5 4 3 5]
arycat.desc: returns the concatenation of arrays A and B

arydup.full:
duplicates the array at the top of the stack
[A] => [A A]

[1 2 3 3] => [1 2 3 3 1 2 3 3]
[7 50 10 2] => [7 50 10 2 50 10 2]
arydup.desc: duplicates the array at the top of the stack

aryeq.full:
returns 1 if the arrays A1 and A2 have the same length and
contain the same elements in the same order, 0 otherwise
[A1 A2] => [0 | 1]

[1 2 3 3 1 2 3 3] => [1]
[1 2 3 3 3 2 1 3] => [0]
[1 2 2 1 2 3 3] => [0]
[1 2 3 3 1 2 2] => [0]
[7 10 2 7 10 2] => [1]
[6 1 9 1] => [0]
aryeq.desc:
returns 1 if the arrays A1 and A2 have the same length and
contain the same elements in the same order, 0 otherwise

aryfill.full:
places an array of N elements E at the top of the stack
[N E] => [A]

[3 0] => [0 0 0 3]
[5 1] => [1 1 1 1 1 5]
[4 -2] => [-2 -2 -2 -2 4]
aryfill.desc: places an array of N elements E at the top of the stack

aryindex.full:
returns the index I of element E in array A (or -1 if not found)
[A E] => [I]

[1 2 3 4 4 2] => [1]
[1 2 3 4 4 4] => [3]
[1 2 3 4 4 5] => [-1]
aryindex.desc: returns the index I of element E in array A (or -1 if not found)

aryinsert.full:
inserts the element E into array A at index I, increasing its length by 1
[A I E] => [A']

[9 5 2 3 1 4] => [9 4 5 2 4]
[1 1 0 7] => [7 1 2]
[3 1 1 7] => [3 7 2]
[7 5 2 1 6] => [7 6 5 3]
aryinsert.desc: inserts the element E into array A at index I, increasing its length by 1

arypop.full:
removes the element at the end of the array A, decreasing its length by 1
[A] => [A']

[10 1] => [0]
[1 2 3 4 4] => [1 2 3 3]
[7 10 20 30 3] => [7 10 20 2]
arypop.desc: removes the element at the end of the array A, decreasing its length by 1

aryprint.full:
prints the array A to stdout in the form [e1,e2,...]
[A] => []
aryprint.desc: prints the array A to stdout in the form [e1,e2,...]

arypush.full:
places the element E at the end of the array A, increasing its length by 1
[A E] => [A']

[3 2 1 3 7] => [3 2 1 7 4]
[4 2 2 0] => [4 2 0 3]
[6 1 9] => [6 9 2]
[7 5 8 2 4] => [7 5 8 4 3]
arypush.desc: places the element E at the end of the array A, increasing its length by 1

aryremove.full:
removes the element at index I in array A, decreasing its length by 1
[A I] => [A']

[6 0 9 3 1] => [6 9 2]
[7 5 3 1 4 0] => [5 3 1 3]
[1 3 5 7 4 3] => [1 3 5 3]
aryremove.desc: removes the element at index I in array A, decreasing its length by 1

aryrep.full:
returns the array A replicated N times
[A N] => [A']

[3 2 1 3 4] => [3 2 1 3 2 1 3 2 1 3 2 1 12]
aryrep.desc: returns the array A replicated N times

aryshift.full:
removes the element at the beginning of the array A, decreasing its length by 1
[A] => [A']

[10 1] => [0]
[1 2 3 4 4] => [2 3 4 3]
[7 10 20 30 3] => [7 20 30 2]
aryshift.desc: removes the element at the beginning of the array A, decreasing its length by 1

arysum.desc: returns the sum of the array A

aryswap.full:
swaps the elements at indices I and J in array A
[A I J] => [A']

[6 0 8 7 4 1 3] => [6 7 8 0 4]
[4 3 2 1 4 0 2] => [2 3 4 1 4]
[3 2 1 3 1 1] => [3 2 1 3]
aryswap.desc: swaps the elements at indices I and J in array A

aryunshift.full:
places the element E at the beginning of the array A, increasing its length by 1
[A E] => [A']

[3 2 1 3 7] => [7 3 2 1 4]
[4 2 0 3 9] => [9 4 2 0 4]
[11 2 2 10] => [10 11 2 3]
[7 2 8 2 0] => [7 0 2 8 3]
aryunshift.desc: places the element E at the beginning of the array A, increasing its length by 1

minmax.full:
returns the minimum and maximum elements of array A
[A] => [min max]

[4 3 2 1 4] => [1 4]
[6 8 -3 4 0 5] => [-3 8]
[7 1] => [7 7]
minmax.desc: returns the minimum and maximum elements of array A

sorted?.full:
returns 0 if any of the elements in array A is
strictly less than the one before it, 1 otherwise
[A] => [0 | 1]

[1 2 3 3] => [1]
[3 2 1 3] => [0]
[1 1 2 2 4] => [1]
[1 2 3 4 3 5] => [0]
sorted?.desc:
returns 0 if any of the elements in array A is
strictly less than the one before it, 1 otherwise

band.desc: returns the bitwise AND of A and B

blength.full:
returns the number of bits in the binary representation of N
[N] => [# of bits]

[0] => [0]   [1] => [1]
[7] => [3]   [8] => [4]
[255] => [8]
blength.desc: returns the number of bits in the binary representation of N

bnot.full:
returns the infinite-precision bitwise NOT of N by inverting all of its bits
[N] => [~N]

[58] => [5]    [46] => [17]
[48] => [15]   [87] => [40]
[98] => [29]   [51] => [12]
[3]  => [0]    [42] => [21]
bnot.desc: returns the infinite-precision bitwise NOT of N by inverting all of its bits

bor.desc: returns the bitwise OR of A and B

bxor.desc: returns the bitwise XOR of A and B

popcount.full:
returns the number of set bits in N
[N] => [popcount]

[0] => [0]   [1] => [1]
[7] => [3]   [8] => [1]
popcount.desc: returns the number of set bits in N

downcase.full:
returns string S with all alphabetical characters lower-cased
[S] => [S']

[""] => [""]
["ABC"] => ["abc"]
["123"] => ["123"]
["aBC123dEF"] => ["abc123def"]
downcase.desc: returns string S with all alphabetical characters lower-cased

swapcase.full:
returns string S with the case of all alphabetical characters swapped
[S] => [S']

[""] => [""]
["FooBar"] => ["fOObAR"]
["Abc123deF"] => ["aBC123DEf"]
swapcase.desc: returns string S with the case of all alphabetical characters swapped

upcase.full:
returns string S with all alphabetical characters capitalized
[S] => [S']

[""] => [""]
["abc"] => ["ABC"]
["123"] => ["123"]
["Abc123Def"] => ["ABC123DEF"]
upcase.desc: returns string S with all alphabetical characters capitalized

ROT13.full:
applies the ROT13 "cipher" to the string S
[S] => [S']

["gnat"] => ["tang"]
["purely"] => ["cheryl"]
["cat.PNG"] => ["png.CAT"]
["Hello, world."] => ["Uryyb, jbeyq."]
["a123z"] => ["n123m"]
ROT13.desc: applies the ROT13 "cipher" to the string S

anagrams?.full:
returns whether the strings S and T are composed of the same characters
[S T] => [0 | 1]

["allergy" "gallery"] => [1]
["largely" "regally"] => [1]
["foo" "bar"] => [0]
anagrams?.desc: returns whether the strings S and T are composed of the same characters

collatz.full:
returns the elements of the Collatz sequence for integer N as a pseudo-array
[N] => [A]

[1] => [1 1]
[2] => [2 1 2]
[3] => [3 10 5 16 8 4 2 1 8]
[4] => [4 2 1 3]
[5] => [5 16 8 4 2 1 6]
collatz.desc: returns the elements of the Collatz sequence for integer N as a pseudo-array

collatz_len.full:
returns the length L of the Collatz sequence for integer N
[N] => [L]

[1] => [1]
[4] => [3]
[7] => [17]
[189] => [107]
collatz_len.desc: returns the length L of the Collatz sequence for integer N

isop.full:
returns the sum of the alphabetical characters in string S where A=1, B=2...
[S] => [sum]

["Math"] => [42]
["wizards"] => [100]
["AbCd"] => [10]
isop.desc: returns the sum of the alphabetical characters in string S where A=1, B=2...

palindrome?.full:
returns whether the string S is the same forwards and backwards
[S] => [0 | 1]

["racecar"] => [1]
["divider"] => [0]
["redivider"] => [1]
palindrome?.desc: returns whether the string S is the same forwards and backwards

to_roman.full:
converts the number N to a string of roman numerals R
[N] => [R]

[2020] => ["MMXX"]
[1666] => ["MDCLXVI"]
[1337] => ["MCCCXXXVII"]
[94] => ["XCIV"]
to_roman.desc: converts the number N to a string of roman numerals R

getline.full:
reads a line of input onto the top of the stack as a packed string
[] => [L]
getline.desc: reads a line of input onto the top of the stack as a packed string

print.full:
prints the character at the top of the stack until terminating zero
[0 ... C] => []
print.desc: prints the character at the top of the stack until terminating zero

prompt.full:
displays the string S then reads a line of input
[S] => [L]
prompt.desc: displays the string S then reads a line of input

readall.full:
consume stdin until EOF into the string S
[] => [S]
readall.desc: consume stdin until EOF into the string S

readfile.full:
returns the contents C of the file at path P (a string)
NON-STANDARD! This function makes use of the `shell` instruction, which is
only(?) available in the Spiceweight Whitespace interpreter.
[P] => [C]
readfile.desc:
returns the contents C of the file at path P (a string)
NON-STANDARD! This function makes use of the `shell` instruction, which is
only(?) available in the Spiceweight Whitespace interpreter.

abs.full:
returns the absolute value of N
[N] => [N < 0 ? -N : N]

[-5] => [5]
[10] => [10]
[0] => [0]
abs.desc: returns the absolute value of N

divisors.full:
returns a pseudo-array of the positive divisors of N; as an optimization,
they're not returned in ascending order, but rather in two "halves".
The alternative is unnecessarily invoking to_a and clobbering heap.
[N] => [D1 ... Dn n]

[10] => [1 2 10 5 4]
[12] => [1 2 3 12 6 4 6]
[25] => [1 5 25 3] ; no duplicate for perfect squares
[60] => [1 2 3 4 5 6 60 30 20 15 12 10 12]
divisors.desc:
returns a pseudo-array of the positive divisors of N; as an optimization,
they're not returned in ascending order, but rather in two "halves".
The alternative is unnecessarily invoking to_a and clobbering heap.

divmod.full:
pops A and B and pushes both their quotient and modulus
[A B] => [A/B A%B]

[17 5] => [3 2]
[42 6] => [7 0]
[ 1 5] => [0 1]
divmod.desc: pops A and B and pushes both their quotient and modulus

factorial.full:
returns the product of the integers from 1 to N, with 0! defined to be 1
[N] => [N!]

[0] => [1],   [1] => [1],     [2] => [2]
[3] => [6],   [5] => [120],   [10] => [3628800]
factorial.desc: returns the product of the integers from 1 to N, with 0! defined to be 1

gcd.full:
returns the greatest common divisor of A and B
[A B] => [gcd(A, B)]

[6 9] => [3]
[13 17] => [1]
[24 36] => [12]
gcd.desc: returns the greatest common divisor of A and B

ilog.full:
returns the intger logarithm of N in base B
[N B] => [logB(N)]

[15   4] => [1]
[16   4] => [2]
[100 10] => [2]
[42   2] => [5]
ilog.desc: returns the intger logarithm of N in base B

isqrt.desc: returns the integer square root of N

lcm.full:
returns the least common multiple of A and B
[A B] => [lcm(A, B)]

[6 9] => [18]
[13 17] => [221]
[24 36] => [72]
lcm.desc: returns the least common multiple of A and B

max.full:
keeps the maximum of the top two stack values
[A B] => [A > B ? A : B]

[3 1] => [3]
[2 4] => [4]
max.desc: keeps the maximum of the top two stack values

min.full:
keeps the minimum of the top two stack values
[A B] => [A < B ? A : B]

[3 1] => [1]
[2 4] => [2]
min.desc: keeps the minimum of the top two stack values

nCk.full:
returns the number of ways to choose K elements from a set of N
[N K]

[ 4 5] => [0]
[ 7 7] => [1]
[13 3] => [286]
[16 4] => [1820]
[50 3] => [19600]
nCk.desc: returns the number of ways to choose K elements from a set of N

neg?.full:
returns whether N is less than 0
[N] => [N < 0]

[5] => [0]   [-3] => [1]   [0] => [0]
neg?.desc: returns whether N is less than 0

pos?.full:
returns whether N is greater than 0
[N] => [N > 0]

[5] => [1]   [-3] => [0]   [0] => [0]
pos?.desc: returns whether N is greater than 0

pow.desc: returns B raised to the power E; if E must be negative, use ratpow instead

sign.desc: returns -1, 0, or 1 to indicate the sign of N

factor.full:
returns the prime factorization of N as a pseudo-array
[N] => [A]

[2] => [2 1]
[8] => [2 2 2 3]
[15] => [3 5 2]
[17] => [17 1]
[100] => [2 2 5 5 4]
factor.desc: returns the prime factorization of N as a pseudo-array

next_prime.full:
returns the first prime number P greater than N
[N] => [P]

[0] => [2]   [1] => [2]
[2] => [3]   [3] => [5]
[13] => [17]
[100] => [101]
next_prime.desc: returns the first prime number P greater than N

prime?.desc: returns 1 if the number N is prime, 0 otherwise

bogosort.full:
sorts the array A if you're lucky
[A] => [A']
bogosort.desc: sorts the array A if you're lucky

dice.full:
returns an array A of N random integers between 1 and D (inclusive)
[N D] => [A]
dice.desc: returns an array A of N random integers between 1 and D (inclusive)

rand.full:
returns the next number N in the linear congruential generator (better MINSTD)
[] => [N]
rand.desc: returns the next number N in the linear congruential generator (better MINSTD)

rand_range.full:
returns a random integer I between A and B (inclusive)
[A B] => [I]
rand_range.desc: returns a random integer I between A and B (inclusive)

shuffle.full:
shuffles the array A in-place using the modern Fisher-Yates algorithm
[A] => [A']
shuffle.desc: shuffles the array A in-place using the modern Fisher-Yates algorithm

srand.full:
seeds the random number generator with integer S
[S] => []
srand.desc: seeds the random number generator with integer S

strfry.full:
shuffles the characters of the string S, producing a random anagram
[S] => [S']
strfry.desc: shuffles the characters of the string S, producing a random anagram

from_r.full:
decomposes the rational number R into its numerator N and denominator D
[R] => [N D]

[R(22,7)] => [22 7]
[R(-3,4)] => [-3 4]
[R(3,-4)] => [-3 4]
[R(4,8)]  => [4 8]  ; no implicit simplification
from_r.desc: decomposes the rational number R into its numerator N and denominator D

ratadd.desc: returns the simplified sum of the rational numbers Ra and Rb

ratden.full:
returns the denominator D of the rational number R; always positive
[R] => [D]

[R(22,7)] => [7]
[R(-3,4)] => [4]
[R(3,-4)] => [4]
ratden.desc: returns the denominator D of the rational number R; always positive

ratdiv.desc: returns the simplified quotient of the rational numbers Ra and Rb

ratinv.full:
returns the simplified inverse of the rational number R
[R] => [1/R]

[R(4,8)] => [R(2,1)]
[R(3,-5)] => [R(-5,3)]
[R(-22,-7)] => [R(7,22)]
ratinv.desc: returns the simplified inverse of the rational number R

ratmod.desc: returns the simplified modulus of the rational numbers Ra and Rb

ratmul.desc: returns the simplified product of the rational numbers Ra and Rb

ratnum.full:
returns the numerator N of the rational number R, which may be negative
[R] => [N]

[R(22,7)] => [22]
[R(-3,4)] => [-3]
[R(3,-4)] => [-3]
ratnum.desc: returns the numerator N of the rational number R, which may be negative

ratpow.desc: returns the rational R raised to the power E

ratsign.desc: returns the sign of the rational number R

ratsimp.full:
fully simplifies the rational number R by dividing both of its components
by their greatest common divisor
[R] => [R, simplified]

[R(4,8)] => [R(1,2)]
[R(-3,12)] => [R(-1,4)]
[R(17,-51)] => [R(-1,3)]
ratsimp.desc:
fully simplifies the rational number R by dividing both of its components
by their greatest common divisor

ratstr.full:
converts the rational number R to a string S of the form
"<simplified numerator>/<simplified denominator>"
[R] => [S]

[R(22,7)] => ["22/7"]
[R(2,4)] => ["1/2"]
[R(99,9)] => ["11/1"]
ratstr.desc:
converts the rational number R to a string S of the form
"<simplified numerator>/<simplified denominator>"

ratsub.desc: returns the simplified difference of the rational numbers Ra and Rb

to_f.full:
converts the rational number R to a "pseudo-float" with a whole (W) part
and a fractional (F) part composed of P digits after the decimal point
[R P] => [W F]

[R(22,7) 2] => [3 14]
[R(355,113) 6] => [3 141592]
[R(8675,309) 10] => [28 744336569] TODO: leading 0 is lost (bug)
[R(2,4) 3] => [0 500]
to_f.desc:
converts the rational number R to a "pseudo-float" with a whole (W) part
and a fractional (F) part composed of P digits after the decimal point

to_r.full:
encodes a numerator N and a denominator D as a rational number R with the
following structure: ((N  $RAT + D) << 1) + sign (0 for negative, else 1).
This representation is nice because, with care, it makes it so that we never
have to involve the heap (besides divmod) just to do fairly basic arithmetic.
[N D] => [R]

[22 7]  => [R(22,7)]
[4 8]   => [R(4,8)]  ; no implicit simplification TODO: make it configurable?
[5 1]   => [R(5,1)]  ; no conversion to integer (duh)
[-3 4]  => [R(-3,4)]
[3 -4]  => [R(-3,4)] ; sign always held in the numerator
[-1 -3] => [R(1,3)]
to_r.desc:
encodes a numerator N and a denominator D as a rational number R with the
following structure: ((N  $RAT + D) << 1) + sign (0 for negative, else 1).
This representation is nice because, with care, it makes it so that we never
have to involve the heap (besides divmod) just to do fairly basic arithmetic.

bury.full:
"buries" X in the stack at index I, counting from 0
[X I]

[1 2 3 4 2] => [1 4 2 3] ; 2nd element of stack now 4
[1 2 3 4 5 8 5] => [8 1 2 3 4 5]
bury.desc: "buries" X in the stack at index I, counting from 0

dig.full:
"digs" out the Ith element of the stack and discards it
[I]

[1 2 3 4 5 2] => [1 2 4 5]
[1 2 3 4 5 4] => [2 3 4 5]
dig.desc: "digs" out the Ith element of the stack and discards it

ncopy.full:
copies the Nth element to the top of the stack; this does exactly what
a `copy N` instruction would do, but we don't always know N in advance
[N]

[1 2 3 4 0] => [1 2 3 4 4] ; `copy 0` is just dup
[1 2 3 4 3] => [1 2 3 4 1]
ncopy.desc:
copies the Nth element to the top of the stack; this does exactly what
a `copy N` instruction would do, but we don't always know N in advance

npop.full:
pops N elements off the top of the stack
[N]

[1 2 3 4 5 3] => [1 2]
[1 2 3 4 0] => [1 2 3 4]
npop.desc: pops N elements off the top of the stack

nslide.full:
slides N elements off the stack, as if the `slide` operator took an argument
[N]

[1 2 3 4 5 2] => [1 2 5]
[1 2 3 4 1] => [1 2 4]
nslide.desc: slides N elements off the stack, as if the `slide` operator took an argument

roll.full:
rolls the Ith element (counting from 0) to the top of the stack,
shifting the elements above it down by 1.
[I]

[1 2 3 2] => [2 3 1]
[1 2 3 4 1] => [1 2 4 3]
[1 2 3 4 5 3] => [1 3 4 5 2]
roll.desc:
rolls the Ith element (counting from 0) to the top of the stack,
shifting the elements above it down by 1.

swapary.desc: swaps the two arrays at the top of the stack

to_a.full:
pops elements off the stack until it hits the specified sentinel value S,
pushing them to the resulting pseudo-array. It's often more convenient to
build up a collection in reverse order, and we often don't know in advance
how many elements we'll meet, but we do know to stop at the sentinel.
[S En ... E1 S] => [E1 ... En n]

[-1 9 8 7 -1] => [7 8 9 3]
[0 'c' 'b' 'a' 0] => ['a' 'b' 'c' 3]
to_a.desc:
pops elements off the stack until it hits the specified sentinel value S,
pushing them to the resulting pseudo-array. It's often more convenient to
build up a collection in reverse order, and we often don't know in advance
how many elements we'll meet, but we do know to stop at the sentinel.

center.full:
centers string S to width W with spaces
[S W] => [S']

["abc" 7] => ["  abc  "]
["abc" 6] => [" abc  "]
["abcd" 6] => [" abcd "]
["abcd" 7] => [" abcd  "]
["abcd" 3] => ["abcd"]
center.desc: centers string S to width W with spaces

centerc.full:
centers string S to width W with character C, favoring left alignment when
there's a parity mismatch (even-length string to odd width or vice versa)
[S W C] => [S']

["abc" 7 'x']  => ["xxabcxx"]
["abc" 6 'x']  => ["xabcxx"]
["abcd" 6 'o'] => ["oabcdo"]
["abcd" 7 'o'] => ["oabcdoo"]
["abcd" 3 '!'] => ["abcd"]
centerc.desc:
centers string S to width W with character C, favoring left alignment when
there's a parity mismatch (even-length string to odd width or vice versa)

charat.full:
returns the character C at index I in string S
[S I] => [C]

["foobar" 1] => ['o']
["foobar" 3] => ['b']
["foobar" 5] => ['r']
["foobar" 6] => [""]
charat.desc: returns the character C at index I in string S

isalpha.full:
returns 1 if the character at the top of the stack is
alphabetical (ASCII 65-90 or 97-122), 0 otherwise
[C] => [0 | 1]

['@'] => [0]   ['a'] => [1]
['z'] => [1]   ['['] => [0]
['`'] => [0]   ['A'] => [1]
['Z'] => [1]   ['{'] => [0]
isalpha.desc:
returns 1 if the character at the top of the stack is
alphabetical (ASCII 65-90 or 97-122), 0 otherwise

lines.full: splits the string S on newlines
lines.effect: splits the string S on newlines

ljust.full:
left-justifies string S to width W with spaces
[S W] => [S']

["foo" 5] => ["foo  "]
["foobar" 4] => ["foobar"]
["" 3] => [528416]
ljust.desc: left-justifies string S to width W with spaces

ljustc.full:
left-justifies string S to width W with character C
[S W C] => [S']

["foo" 5 'x'] => ["fooxx"]
["foobar" 4 'x'] => ["foobar"]
["" 3 'x'] => ["xxx"]
ljustc.desc: left-justifies string S to width W with character C

memfrob.full:
frobnicates the string S by XORing all its bytes with 42
[S] => [S']

["foobar"] => ["LEEHKX"]
["LEEHKX"] => ["foobar"]
memfrob.desc: frobnicates the string S by XORing all its bytes with 42

rjust.full:
right-justifies string S to width W with spaces
[S W C] => [S']

["foo" 5] => ["  foo"]
["foobar" 4] => ["foobar"]
["" 3] => [528416]
rjust.desc: right-justifies string S to width W with spaces

rjustc.full:
right-justifies string S to width W with character C
[S W C] => [S']

["foo" 5 'x'] => ["xxfoo"]
["foobar" 4 'x'] => ["foobar"]
["" 3 'x'] => ["xxx"]
rjustc.desc: right-justifies string S to width W with character C

strcat.full:
takes two packed strings and returns their concatenation (as a packed string)
[S T] => [S+T]

["foo" ""] => ["foo"]
["" "foo"] => ["foo"]
["foo" "bar"] => ["foobar"]
strcat.desc: takes two packed strings and returns their concatenation (as a packed string)

strchop.full:
removes the last character of a string
[S] => [S']

["foobar"] => ["fooba"]
["abc"] => ["ab"]
["a"] => [""]
[""] => [""]
strchop.desc: removes the last character of a string

strcount.full:
returns the total number of ocurrences of all characters in string T in string S
[S T] => [N]

["foobar" 'o'] => [2]
["foobar" "ob"] => [3]
["foxboar" "box"] => [4]
["eunoia" "aeiou"] => [5]
["why" "aeiou"] => [0]
strcount.desc: returns the total number of ocurrences of all characters in string T in string S

strcountc.full:
returns the number of ocurrences of character C in string S
[S C] => [N]

["foobar" 'a'] => [1]
["foobar" 'o'] => [2]
["foobar" 'c'] => [0]
strcountc.desc: returns the number of ocurrences of character C in string S

strdel.full:
returns the string S with all characters in string T removed, like `tr -d`.
If the first character of T is '^', instead only those characters are kept.
[S T] => [S']

["abc123" "abc"] => ["123"]
["abc123" "123"] => ["abc"]
["abcba12321" "abc"] => ["12321"]
["abc12321cba" "^2ac"] => ["ac22ca"]
["facetious" "^aeiou"] => ["aeiou"]
strdel.desc:
returns the string S with all characters in string T removed, like `tr -d`.
If the first character of T is '^', instead only those characters are kept.

strexpand.full:
expands the length-2 string S to contain the intervening ASCII characters
[S] => [S']

["CJ"] => ["CDEFGHIJ"]
["DA"] => ["DCBA"]
["af"] => ["abcdef"]
["09"] => ["0123456789"]
["90"] => ["9876543210"]
["(1"] => ["()*+,-./01"]
strexpand.desc: expands the length-2 string S to contain the intervening ASCII characters

strindex.full:
returns the index I of substring T in string S (or -1 if not found)
[S T] => [I]

["foobar" 'o'] => [1]
["foobar" "ob"] => [2]
["foobar" ""] => [0]
["foobar" "bar"] => [3]
["foobar" "bark"] => [-1]
strindex.desc: returns the index I of substring T in string S (or -1 if not found)

strjoin.full:
concatenates the pseudo-array of strings A into string S
[A] => [S]

["foo" 1] => ["foo"]
["foo" "bar" 2] => ["foobar"]
["foo" 'x' "bar" 'x' "baz" 5] => ["fooxbarxbaz"]
strjoin.desc: concatenates the pseudo-array of strings A into string S

strjoinc.full:
joins the pseudo-array of strings A into string S with delimiter string D
[A D] => [S]

["foo" "bar" 2 'x'] => ["fooxbar"]
["foo" "bar" "baz" 3 '--'] => ["foo--bar--baz"]
["foo" 1 "?!"] => ["foo"]
strjoinc.desc: joins the pseudo-array of strings A into string S with delimiter string D

strlen.full:
returns the length of a packed string, which is just the
value itself log-128, +1 if the integer logarithm isn't exact.
[S] => [len(S)]

[""] => [0]
["abc"] => [3]
["foobar"] => [6]
strlen.desc:
returns the length of a packed string, which is just the
value itself log-128, +1 if the integer logarithm isn't exact.

strpack.full:
convert a 0-terminated string on the stack to a single base-128 integer
[0 ... c b a] => ["abc..."]

[0 99 98 97] => ["abc"]
[0 99 98 97] => [1634657]
[0] => [0]
strpack.desc: convert a 0-terminated string on the stack to a single base-128 integer

strrep.full:
returns string S replicated N times
[S N] => [S']

["abc" 1] => ["abc"]
["abc" 2] => ["abcabc"]
["abc" 0] => [""]
strrep.desc: returns string S replicated N times

strrotl.full:
rotates the string S to the left N times, wrapping
[S N] => [S']

["abc" 0] => ["abc"]
["abcd" 1] => ["bcda"]
["abcd" 5] => ["bcda"]
["foodbar" 4] => ["barfood"]
strrotl.desc: rotates the string S to the left N times, wrapping

strrotr.full:
rotates the string S to the right N times, wrapping
[S N] => [S']

["abcd" 1] => ["dabc"]
["abcd" 5] => ["dabc"]
["foodbar" 3] => ["barfood"]
strrotr.desc: rotates the string S to the right N times, wrapping

strslice.full:
takes a packed string S, a start index I, and a length L and returns the
corresponding substring (simply by doing division with powers of 128; neat)
[S I L] => [S']

["foobar" 0  6] => ["foobar"]
["foobar" 1  4] => ["ooba"]
["foobar" 1 10] => ["oobar"]
["foobar" 5  1] => ['r']
["foobar" 6  0] => [""]
strslice.desc:
takes a packed string S, a start index I, and a length L and returns the
corresponding substring (simply by doing division with powers of 128; neat)

strsplit.full:
splits string S on delimiting character C, leaving the resultant substrings
on the stack as a pseudo-array (length at top of stack)
[S C] => [A]

["fooxbar" 'x'] => ["foo" "bar" 2]
["foobar" 'x'] => ["foobar" 1]
["foo|bar|baz" '|'] => ["foo" "bar" "baz" 3]
["foo,,bar" ','] => ["foo" "" "bar" 3]
["/foo/bar/" '/'] => ["" "foo" "bar" "" 4]
strsplit.desc:
splits string S on delimiting character C, leaving the resultant substrings
on the stack as a pseudo-array (length at top of stack)

strsqueeze.full:
"squeezes" runs of the same character in string S to just one occurrence
[S] => [S']

["abc"] => ["abc"]
["foobar"] => ["fobar"]
["bookkeeper"] => ["bokeper"]
["xxxxxxx"] => ["x"]
strsqueeze.desc: "squeezes" runs of the same character in string S to just one occurrence

strsum.full:
returns the sum of the ordinal values of the characters in string S
[S] => [N]

["ABC"] => [198]
["012"] => [147]
["a"] => [97]
[""] => [0]
strsum.desc: returns the sum of the ordinal values of the characters in string S

strtoa.full:
gets the characters of the string S onto the stack as a pseudo-array, but
with a leading 0 on the assumption that it'll eventually be repacked

["abc"] => [0 99 98 97 3]
strtoa.desc: gets the characters of the string S onto the stack as a pseudo-array, but
strtoa.effect: with a leading 0 on the assumption that it'll eventually be repacked

strtrans.full:
translates all characters in A to the corresponding characters in B
in string S, ; similar to the `tr` utility in Unix. A and B must be
of the same length. TODO: make this smarter (ranges, length mismatch)
[S A B] => [S']

["abcd" "abc" "xyz"] => ["xyzd"]
["foobar" "oba" "ele"] => ["feeler"]
["abcdcba" "abcd" "xyz|"] => ["xyz|zyx"]
strtrans.desc:
translates all characters in A to the corresponding characters in B
in string S, ; similar to the `tr` utility in Unix. A and B must be
of the same length. TODO: make this smarter (ranges, length mismatch)

strunpack.full:
convert a single base-128 integer to a 0-terminated string on the stack
["abc..."] => [0 ... c b a]

["abc"] => [0 99 98 97]
[1634657] => [0 99 98 97]
[0] => [0]
strunpack.desc: convert a single base-128 integer to a 0-terminated string on the stack

aryheap.full:
stashes the array A in negative heap space starting at index I
[A I] => []
aryheap.desc: stashes the array A in negative heap space starting at index I

between?.full:
returns 1 if the number N is between A and B (inclusive), 0 otherwise
[N A B]

[5 0 10] => [1]
[11 0 10] => [0]
[4 0 4] => [1]
[-1 0 4] => [0]
[-5 -10 0] => [1]
[3 4 2] => [0]
between?.desc: returns 1 if the number N is between A and B (inclusive), 0 otherwise

dec.full:
decrements the value at heap address N
[N]
dec.desc: decrements the value at heap address N

die!.full:
prints the string at the top of the stack and halts execution after pushing
something onto the stack to signal abnormal termination/unclean exit
[...] => [... 1]
die!.desc:
prints the string at the top of the stack and halts execution after pushing
something onto the stack to signal abnormal termination/unclean exit

digits.full:
puts the digits of N in base B on the stack as a pseudo-array
[N B] => [Dn ...D0 n]

[42 2] => [1 0 1 0 1 0 6]
[12345 10] => [1 2 3 4 5 5]
[255 16] => [15 15 2]
[256 16] => [1 0 0 3]
digits.desc: puts the digits of N in base B on the stack as a pseudo-array

eq.full:
pops A and B and pushes 1 if they're equal, 0 otherwise
[A B] => [A == B]

[1 2] => [0]
[3 3] => [1]
[-4 4] => [0]
['A' 65] => [1]
['B' 65] => [0]
eq.desc: pops A and B and pushes 1 if they're equal, 0 otherwise

gt.full:
pops A and B and pushes 1 if A is greater than B, 0 otherwise
[A B] => [A > B]

[4 3] => [1]   [3 4] => [0]
[2 2] => [0]   [2 1] => [1]
gt.desc: pops A and B and pushes 1 if A is greater than B, 0 otherwise

gte.full:
pops A and B and pushes 1 if A is greater than or equal to B, 0 otherwise
[A B] => [A > B]

[2 2] => [1]   [1 2] => [0]
[3 4] => [0]   [4 3] => [1]
gte.desc: pops A and B and pushes 1 if A is greater than or equal to B, 0 otherwise

heap-seeking_missile.full:
Though extremely rare, it's possible that we know a particular value is
stored in the heap at some key, just not which one. This subroutine takes
a value V to search for and a starting index I, and either returns the first
key associated with that value or loops forever. Probably don't touch.
[V I]
heap-seeking_missile.desc:
Though extremely rare, it's possible that we know a particular value is
stored in the heap at some key, just not which one. This subroutine takes
a value V to search for and a starting index I, and either returns the first
key associated with that value or loops forever. Probably don't touch.

heapary.full:
restores the heaped array starting at index I
[I] => [A]
heapary.desc: restores the heaped array starting at index I

heapswap.full:
swaps the elements in the heap at indices I and J
[I J] => []
heapswap.desc: swaps the elements in the heap at indices I and J

hex2rgb.full:
converts the #RRGGBB (leading '#' optional) color string S to
its individual RGB components as integers in the range 0-255
[S] => [R G B]

["#000000"] => [0 0 0]
["ffffff"]  => [255 255 255]
["#102030"] => [16 32 48]
["c0ffee"] => [192 255 238]
hex2rgb.desc:
converts the #RRGGBB (leading '#' optional) color string S to
its individual RGB components as integers in the range 0-255

inc.full:
increments the value at heap address N TODO: make heap effects test-able ?
[N]
inc.desc: increments the value at heap address N TODO: make heap effects test-able ?

itos.desc: converts the integer N to a string in base B

lt.full:
pops A and B and pushes 1 if A is less than than B, 0 otherwise
[A B] => [A < B]

[3 4] => [1]   [4 3] => [0]
[2 2] => [0]   [1 2] => [1]
lt.desc: pops A and B and pushes 1 if A is less than than B, 0 otherwise

lte.full:
pops A and B and pushes 1 if A is less than or equal to B, 0 otherwise
[A B] => [A > B]

[2 2] => [1]   [2 1] => [0]
[4 3] => [0]   [3 4] => [1]
lte.desc: pops A and B and pushes 1 if A is less than or equal to B, 0 otherwise

neq.full:
pops A and B and pushes 1 if they're not equal, 0 otherwise
[A B] => [A != B]

[1 2] => [1]
[3 3] => [0]
[-4 4] => [1]
['A' 65] => [0]
['B' 65] => [1]
neq.desc: pops A and B and pushes 1 if they're not equal, 0 otherwise

range.full:
inserts between the top two stack values the intervening consecutive elements
supports counting up or down
[I J] => [I I1 ... J]

[2 5] => [2 3 4 5]
[5 2] => [5 4 3 2]
[0 4] => [0 1 2 3 4]
[4 0] => [4 3 2 1 0]
[-2 0] => [-2 -1 0]
[0 -2] => [0 -1 -2]
[-3 3] => [-3 -2 -1 0 1 2 3]
[3 -3] => [3 2 1 0 -1 -2 -3]
[4 4] => [4]
range.desc:
inserts between the top two stack values the intervening consecutive elements
supports counting up or down

rgb2hex.full:
converts R, G, and B components to length-6 hexadecimal string S
[R G B] => [S]

[0 0 0] => ["000000"]
[255 255 255] => ["ffffff"]
[16 32 48] => ["102030"]
[192 255 238] => ["c0ffee"]
rgb2hex.desc: converts R, G, and B components to length-6 hexadecimal string S

steprange.desc:
inserts between I and J the intervening consecutive elements, counting by
step S up/down to (but never beyond) J

stoi.desc: converts the string S to an integer in base B (2-36)
